[[File:Ancient Graves in Wahi Pandhi.jpg|thumb|Ancient Graves in Wahi Pandhi]] [[File:The word "Behdin" is inscribed on stone of Ancient Graves in Wahi Pandhi.jpg|thumb|The word "Behdin" is inscribed on stone of Ancient Graves in Wahi Pandhi]] [[File:A columned Ancient Grave in Wahi Pandhi.jpg|thumb|A columned Ancient Grave in Wahi Pandhi]] [[File:Bones of Corpse are placed in columned grave at Ancient Graves in Wahi Pandhi.jpg|thumb|Bones of Corpse are placed in columned grave at Ancient Graves in Wahi Pandhi]] The '''Ancient Graves''' are situated near [[Wahi Pandhi]], [[Johi, Dadu|Johi]] tehsil, [[Dadu District]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]], on the top of the hills near foothills of [[Kirthar Mountains]] Range. These columned graves are constructed with large slabs of stone on ground surface. The graves are open from northern and southern sides. The western and eastern sides of graves are constructed with stone slabs and also the graves are covered from upper side with slabs. The carpse were placed on ground surface in the graves. The bones can be observed in columned graves on ground surfaces in graves. Due to inscribed word "Behdin"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/behdin-the-good-religion|title=BEHDĪN – Encyclopaedia Iranica|first=|last=electricpulp.com|website=www.iranicaonline.org}}</ref> on stone of one grave, it is believed that these ancient graves belonged to [[Zoroastrians]].<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/754686|title=Heritage: The ancient graves|first=From|last=InpaperMagazine|date=6 October 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1500279/tomb-raiders-leave-little-sindhs-heritage-intact/|title=Tomb raiders leave little of Sindh's heritage intact - The Express Tribune|date=10 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The word behdin means the good religion which is related to [[Zoroastrianism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=oaSHIlcRejEC&pg=PA226&lpg=PA226&dq=behdin+means&source=bl&ots=4kVAj_yBy9&sig=TXQh6aNzsKgQXhTb3bCapVsvuic&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwif-uiW9afZAhUFo48KHXl5C2IQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q=behdin+means&f=false|title=Qiṣṣah-i Sanjān|first=Alan|last=Williams|date=3 March 2018|publisher=BRILL|via=Google Books}}</ref>
==History==
Two Burial places of the ancient graves in Wahi Pandhi are sited along the both banks of Narri or Nalli hilly torrent are locally called roman’s graves. The both necropolises can be counted of different periods.<ref name=":0" /> The awning of Smail Fakir is sole monument of the desert of [[Kachho]] which is constructed with heavy carved pillars without any material. The Ceiling stones of canopy are expertly engraved with gorgeous Sun like structure.<ref name=":0" /> The graves are built with yellowish stone blocks. It seems no any material was used for fitting stone slabs together with. Many memorial names and other inscriptions are inscribed on stones to be belied in Kufi or [[Persian language]] script.<ref name=":0" /> It is believed that these belong to the invading period of Alexander the great and some scholars are of the opinion that these ancient graves belong to [[Baloch (surname)]] tribe but question arises that which Baloch tribe had tradition to keep corpse in open or columned graves with carved stone slabs .Bherumal Maharchan Adwani considers the graves of Zoroastrians. In Sindh, invasion of Persia [[Iran]] can be traced from Daruish-1.<ref name="Encyclopedia Britannica">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Zoroastrianism|title=Zoroastrianism {{!}} Definition, Beliefs, Founder, & Facts|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-04-07|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> In 637 AD, during the battle of Qadisia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historyworld.net/wrldhis/PlainTextHistories.asp?historyid=ab71|title=HISTORY OF ZOROASTRIANISM|website=www.historyworld.net|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> the Muslims invaded Persia. The Zoroastrians were called Gabrs in the reflection Gabr, the Zoroastrians called themselves Behdin or Bahadin. Many [[Gabr]] or Gabar as well [[Givar]] Bands are constructed near hilly torrents for collecting waters in [[Kirthar Mountains]] Range which indicate to Zoroastrians.<ref name=":0" /> Zoroastrians or Parsis still live in [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/808297/decline-in-population-of-zoroastrian-descent/|title=Decline in population: Of Zoroastrian descent - The Express Tribune|date=2014-12-21|work=The Express Tribune|access-date=2018-04-07|language=en-US}}</ref> including [[India]].<ref name="Encyclopedia Britannica"/> History reveals that Zoroastrians or Parsis migrated from [[Iran]] to [[Punjab, Pakistan]] and [[Sindh]] Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zamwi.org/zoroastrianism/|title=About Zoroastrianism – Zoroastrian Association of Metropolitan Washington Inc.|website=zamwi.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref>
