'''''On Colors''''' (Greek Περὶ χρωμάτων; Latin ''De Coloribus'') is a treatise attributed to [[Aristotle]]<ref>Barnes, Jonathan (1984).  ''The Complete Works of Aristotle'' (2 Vols.), Princeton University Press, pp. 1219-1228 (V 1).  {{ISBN|0-691-01650-X}}.</ref> but sometimes ascribed to [[Theophrastus]] or [[Strato of Lampsacus|Strato]]. The work outlines the theory that all [[colors]] (yellow, red, purple, green, and blue) are derived from mixtures of black and white. ''On colors'' had a pronounced impact on subsequent [[Color Theory|color theories]] and remained influential until [[Isaac Newton]]'s experiments with light refraction.  

